":"1205","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","22 January 1156":"22 januari 1156","1056":"1056","1100":"1100","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","about 1100":"circa 1100","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"about 1100–1200":"about 1100–1200","1100–1200":"1100–1200","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","1142–1205":"1142–1205","1156–Male":"1156–Deceased","1056–Male":"1056–Deceased","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","22 January 1156":"22 January 1156","1056":"1056","1100":"1100","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","about 1100":"about 1100","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Booth,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>bothe</i> (Old Danish <i>bōth</i>) ‘temporary shelter, such as a covered market stall or a cattle-herdsman's hut’. The latter sense was predominant in the Pennines of Lancashire and Yorkshire, where there were many cattle farms or vaccaries, and whose subdivisions were known as ‘booths’. The principal meaning of the surname there was therefore probably ‘cattle herdsman’, ‘man in charge of a vaccary’, and thus identical with   Boothman  . Elsewhere it may have denoted a shopkeeper who owned a temporary market stall, but no evidence has been found to confirm this use of the surname. In the British Isles the surname is still more common in northern England, where Scandinavian influence was more marked, and in Scotland, where the word was borrowed into Gaelic as <i>both(an)</i>.","History: Robert Booth (1604–72) is mentioned in the colonial records of Exeter, NH, in 1645. He subsequently moved to ME."],"variants":[{"name":"Boothman","meanings":["English (northern): occupational name from Middle English <i>both</i> (Old Danish <i>bōth</i>) ‘temporary shelter, such as a covered market stall or a cattle-herdsman's hut’ + <i>man</i>. In the Pennine uplands of northern England, where booths were subdivisons of vaccaries or cattle-rearing establishment, the name probably denoted a herdsman who looked after cattle, perhaps a man in charge of a vaccary. Elsewhere the surname might have denoted a shopkeeper but evidence for this lacking. Alternatively, the name can also be an occupational name for a servant of a man surnamed   Booth  ."]},{"name":"Boothe","meanings":["English: variant of   Booth  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Booth, Saxon Thane was born about 1100, in England, his father, ELDRED Thane, was 45 and his mother, Wife Thane, was 21. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Wife Thane. He died in 1200, at the age of 101."},"et":{"about 1100–1200":"umbes 1100–1200","1100–1200":"1100–1200","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1142–1205":"1142–1205","1156–Male":"1156–Surnud","1056–Male":"1056–Surnud","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","22 January 1156":"22. jaanuar 1156","1056":"1056","1100":"1100","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","about 1100":"umbes 1100","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1100–1200":"noin 1100–1200","1100–1200":"1100–1200","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","1142–1205":"1142–1205","1156–Male":"1156–Kuollut","1056–Male":"1056–Kuollut","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1205":"1205","1200":"1200","1156":"1156","22 January 1156":"22. tammikuuta 1156","1056":"1056","1100":"1100","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","about 1100":"noin 1100","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"about 1100–1200":"environ 1100–